To elucidate the slight blue-shift of the THG peak from the fundamental MD wavelength, as well as appearance of the side small peak observed, in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2}(c) we plot contributions from the MD $a_M(1,0)$, $\propto 3 |a_{M}(1,0)|^2/k_0^2 $, and MO $a_M(3,0)$, $\propto 7 |a_{M}(3,0)|^2/k_0^2 $, into the linear scattering over the wide range of wavelengths, based on the exact Mie solution. Each multipole has an infinite number of resonances. From the above analysis, we expect only two multipoles to dominate others in the nonlinear response and visualize the spectral disposition of the generated modes around the tripled frequency. The small side peak is seen to be 
associated with the octupole resonance near the tripled frequency.




The power dependencies on wavelength depicted in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2}(b) were found to be consistent
with the results of numerical calculations performed with the help of the finite-element method (FEM) solver COMSOL Multiphysics (see the METHODS section for details).




In our simulations, the homogeneous host medium was described by the relative dielectric permittivity ${\varepsilon}_{1r} = 1$. 


For the particle of $n=3.5$, numerically calculated at the MD resonance nonlinear source and TH generated field distributions are demonstrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2_2}(a). Naturally, the depicted nonlinear current, being essentially the cubed field of the MD mode excited by the pump wave, possesses a notable magnetic dipole moment. As seen in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2_2}(b), close to the MD resonance results obtained for THG with the use of COMSOL still fit well into our 
analytical model that

may be regarded as a shortcut of the more involved treatment exploiting the Green's function formalism~\cite{Biris2010}. Within the broad MD resonance, both magnetic dipole and magnetic octupole contribute to the THG peak, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2_2}(c). This explains the six-petalled TH near-field structure in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2_2}(a).


