\section*{METHODS} \label{sec:Methods}


{\bf Multipole decomposition.} We adopt the following well-established standard form of the multipole expansion for the scattered (or radiated) field written in the spherical coordinates~\cite{Jackson1965,Grahn2012} (accepting harmonic time-dependence $\sim e^{-i\omega t}$):

\begin{eqnarray}
{\bf E}_{s}\left( {\omega;r,\theta ,\varphi } \right) = E_0\sum_{l=1}^{\infty}\sum_{m=-l}^l i^l\sqrt{\pi (2l+1)}
\Big\{ a_{{M}}(l,m)h_l^{(1)}(kr){\bf X}_{lm}(\theta,\varphi)   \nonumber \\
+ \frac{1}{k}a_{{E}}(l,m)\nabla\times \big[h_l^{(1)}(kr){\bf X}_{lm}(\theta,\varphi)\big]\Big\}, \\
{\bf H}_{{s}}\left( {\omega;r,\theta ,\varphi } \right) = \frac{E_0}{\eta}\sum_{l=1}^{\infty}\sum_{m=-l}^l i^{l-1}\sqrt{\pi (2l+1)}
\Big\{ a_{{E}}(l,m) h_l^{(1)}(kr){\bf X}_{lm}(\theta,\varphi)  \nonumber \\
+\frac{1}{k}a_{{M}}(l,m)\nabla\times\big[h_l^{(1)}(kr){\bf X}_{lm}(\theta,\varphi)\big] \Big\},
\end{eqnarray}

where ${\bf{X}}_{l,m} = {\displaystyle\frac}{-1}{\sqrt{l(l+1)}} \biggl\{ 0, {\displaystyle\frac}{mY_{l,m}(\theta, {\varphi})}{\sin{\theta}},i{\displaystyle\frac}{\partial Y_{l,m}(\theta, {\varphi})}{\partial \theta} \biggr\}$ are the vector spherical harmonics expressed through the scalar spherical harmonics $Y_{l,m}(\theta, {\varphi})$, $h_l^{(1)}$ are the spherical Hankel functions of the first kind with the asymptotics of outgoing spherical waves, $k=\omega\sqrt{{\varepsilon}\mu} \equiv k_0 \sqrt{{\varepsilon}_{r}\mu_{r}}$ is the wavenumber in the medium, $\eta = \sqrt{\mu/{\varepsilon}}$ is the impedance,
$E_0$ is an electric field amplitude factor.

The electric $a_{{E}}(l,m)$ and magnetic $a_{{M}}(l,m)$ multipole cofficients can be found 
either through the volume integration of the source current density distribution, or by using angular integrals of radial components of the numerically pre-calculated scattered field over a spherical surface of some radius $r$ enclosing an isolated scatterer as follows:
\begin{subequations}
\label{eq:aEaM}

text:
\begin{equation}
C^{(l)}_2 =
I^{(l)}  \left[{\displaystyle\frac}{j_l( {K}_{2} a) {\displaystyle\frac}{d y_l( {K}_{2} r)}{dr}\Biggr|_{\substack{r=a}}   -  y_l( {K}_{2} a)  {\displaystyle\frac}{d j_l( {K}_{2} r)}{dr}\Biggr|_{\substack{r=a}}  }
{j_l( {K}_{2} a)  {\displaystyle\frac}{d h_l^{(1)}( {K}_{1} r)}{dr}\Biggr|_{\substack{r=a}}    - h_l^{(1)}( {K}_{1} a)  {\displaystyle\frac}{d j_l( {K}_{2} r)}{dr}\Biggr|_{\substack{r=a}}   } \right]
\:.
\end{equation}

prevtext:
Using the asymptotics $h_l^{(1)}( {K}_{1} r) \sim (-i)^{l+1}{\displaystyle\frac}{e^{iK_1 r}}{K_1 r}$ in Eqs.~\eqref{eq:E_TH},~\eqref{eq:solradE} in the far-field zone allows one to determine 
the directional dependence of the TH radiation $D_{3\omega} (\theta,\varphi)$, as well as the total radiated energy flux.
The calculated resonant curve of the TH generated power is plotted in Fig.~\ref{fig:fig2}(b) as a function of the wavelength of the incident wave, where we also demonstrate variations of the TH emission pattern, originating from the interference of MD and MO, though preserving azimuthal symmetry. 


